unted examines the phenomenon of disenfranchisement through the lens of history, race, law, and the democratic process. Gilda R. Daniels, who served as Deputy Chief in the United States Department of Justice Civil Rights Division and more than two decades of voting rights experience, argues that voter suppression works in cycles, constantly adapting and finding new ways to hinder access for an exponentially growing minority population. She warns that a premeditated strategy of restrictive laws and deceptive practices has taken root and is eroding the very basis of American democracy—the right to vote!  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aElectionsxCorrupt practiceszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aElectionsxCorrupt practiceszUnited States. 0aSuffragezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSuffragezUnited States. 0aVoter registrationxCorrupt practiceszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aVoter registrationxCorrupt practiceszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh  aactivism.  aadvocacy.  aafrican american.  aamerican citizens.  aconstitutional rights.  ademocracy.  ademocratic party.  adiscrimination.  afelon disenfranchisement.  agerrymandering.  agrandfather clauses.  aid requirements.  aliteracy test.  aminority voters.  apoll tax.  aracial justice.  arepublican party.  arigged elections.  ashelby ruling.  avoter fraud.  avoter initmidation.  avoter restrictions.  avoting rights act.  avoting rights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBoo